05292nam a22009255i 9780823288335DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20202020nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232883357 a10.1515/97808232883352doi  a(DE-B1597)566206  a(OCoLC)1154572260  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aREL0670202bisacsh1 aPryor, Adam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiving with Tiny Aliens :bThe Image of God for the Anthropocene /cAdam Pryor. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGroundworks: Ecological Issues in Philosophy and Theology00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Being in Outer Space -- t1. Exoplanets and Icy Moons and Mars, Oh My! -- t2. Astrobiology’s Intra-Active Aliens -- t3. Being a Living-System -- t4. The imago Dei as a Refractive Symbol -- t5. Conceptualizing Nature -- t6. The Anthropocene as Planetarity in Deep Time -- t7. An Artful Planet -- t8. Living-Into Presence, Wonder, and Play -- tEpilogue: Ad Astra Per Aspera -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAstrobiology is changing how we understand meaningful human existence. Living with Tiny Aliens seeks to imagine how an individuals’ meaningful existence persists when we are planetary creatures situated in deep time—not only on a blue planet burgeoning with life, but in a cosmos pregnant with living-possibilities. In doing so, it works to articulate an astrobiological humanities.Working with a series of specific examples drawn from the study of extraterrestrial life, doctrinal reflection on the imago Dei, and reflections on the Anthropocene, Pryor reframes how human beings meaningfully dwell in the world and belong to it. To take seriously the geological significance of human agency is to understand the Earth as not only a living planet but an artful one. Consequently, Pryor reframes the imago Dei, rendering it a planetary system that opens up new possibilities for the flourishing of all creation by fostering technobiogeochemical cycles not subject to runaway, positive feedback. Such an account ensures the imago Dei is not something any one of us possesses, but that it is a symbol for what we live into together as a species in intra-action with the wider habitable environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aExobiologyxReligious aspects. 0aImage of God. 0aTheological anthropology. 4aReligion. 4aScience Studies. 4aTheology. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / Anthropology.2bisacsh  aAnthropocene.  aAstrobiology.  aDavid Grinspoon.  aKaren Barad.  aMaurice Merleau-Ponty.  aflesh.  ahabitability.  aimage of God.  aimago Dei.  aintra-action.  aplay.  apresence.  awonder.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020z9783110704570oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311072271040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823288335zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823288335423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823288335/original  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070477-8  EBOOK PA